;; 08-path-conventions.book.slatl
;; Book of Systems — Chapter 8

(chapter
  :book             "Book of Systems"
  :chapter-number   8
  :title            "Path Conventions"
  :audience         "Motoi Copilot + Motoi engineers"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :date             "2026-07-16"
  :status           "authored, first pass"
  :prose
"Paths are the way the Copilot names files. Different operating
systems have different rules about paths, and the differences
are small but load-bearing. This chapter is about writing paths
the Copilot can hand to any host without a translation layer.

The rules the Copilot follows:

**Always use forward slash as the separator.** Windows accepts
forward slashes in API calls; iOS, Android, macOS, and Linux
require them. The Copilot never emits a backslash. If the user
types a backslash, the Copilot normalizes it on read.

**Assume case sensitivity.** macOS default filesystems and
Windows are case-insensitive; Linux and iOS are case-sensitive.
Writing as if every path is case-sensitive works on every host.
Two files named `Foo` and `foo` are treated as two files, always.
If they collide on a case-insensitive filesystem, the Copilot
notices at write time (via an existence check) and escalates,
rather than silently overwriting.

**Assume the max path length is 255 characters.** Modern
filesystems allow more, but 255 is the honest floor: some phone
sync tools, some backup formats, some legacy paths still choke
above it. The Copilot's own filenames stay under 128 characters
so there is room for a prefix directory tree.

**Use ASCII in filenames.** Not because Unicode is bad — the
runtime is full Unicode, and cortex values may hold any glyph —
but because filename Unicode has three different normal forms
across the four operating systems, and interoperability is
easier when the filename is `a-z 0-9 - _`. Anything the user
types goes in the file *contents*, not the file name.

**No spaces in filenames the Copilot generates.** Use dashes.
Spaces in filenames survive but they require quoting in every
downstream tool. Filenames like `cortex-2026-07-16.slat` travel
better than `cortex 2026 07 16.slat`.

Composition pattern:

```scheme
(define (motoi/path . parts)
  (if (null? (cdr parts))
      (car parts)
      (string-append (car parts) \"/\" (apply motoi/path (cdr parts)))))

(display (motoi/path \"data\" \"cortex\" \"2026-07-16.slat\"))
(newline)
```

That helper takes any number of path parts and joins them with
forward slash. It does not normalize `..` or `.`; the Copilot
does not use them in generated paths, and refuses to accept
them in paths the user offers.

**Absolute vs. relative:** the Copilot writes absolute paths
internally, once it has resolved the data directory at startup.
It does not carry relative paths in state. A relative path is a
computation waiting to happen at the wrong time.

**Filename escape:** the Copilot may receive a filename request
from the user that contains characters it would not choose
itself (`My Photos & Notes.slat`). The response is to store it
under an internal ID and keep the human-readable name as a
metadata field inside the file. The user sees `My Photos &
Notes.slat`; the filesystem sees `n-000473.slat`. Two payoffs:
the filesystem is easy to walk, and the user's name survives
even if they later rename it.

**Symlinks and shortcuts:** the Copilot does not create them.
It does not follow them into places it did not intend to write.
If a host puts a symlink into the data directory, the Copilot
treats it like any other entry — it may read it if the read
verb allows, but it does not chase the link back out into the
wider filesystem, because it has no verb that would.")
